.TH GIT-PR 1 "2026-07-07" "git-tools" "Git Tools Manual"
.SH NAME
git-pr \- check out the branch for a GitHub pull request by number
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git pr
.I NUMBER
.br
.B git pr
[\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Check out the head branch of GitHub pull request #\fINUMBER\fR. If that branch
already exists locally,
.B git pr
just switches to it; otherwise it fetches it first. For merged or closed PRs
whose branch has been deleted from
.IR origin ,
it falls back to
.IR refs/pull/<NUMBER>/head ,
which GitHub keeps around, into a local branch of the same name.
.PP
Branches checked out this way are stamped with their PR number
.RB ( "branch.<name>.gtools-pr" ),
so a later
.B git pr
for the same number resolves the branch offline and switches to it with no
.B gh
call. The GitHub CLI is consulted only to resolve or fetch a branch you do not
already have.
.PP
Named
.I git pr
rather than
.IR git switch :
git always prefers its built-in
.B switch
over a script, so a custom
.I git-switch
could never run.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage and exit.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
Requires the GitHub CLI
.RB ( gh ),
authenticated for the repository
.RB ( "gh auth login" ),
except when switching to an already-stamped branch, which needs no network.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B git pr 923
Check out the head branch of PR #923.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git-done (1),
.BR git-sync (1),
.BR git-sweep (1),
.BR gh (1)
